  "description": "<h2 id=\"introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<p>Many consider these \"the best anasazi cliff dwellings in the region,\nafter Mesa Verde\". The ruins are very well preserved, with an interior\npatio that conserves the original roof and room structures, even some of\nthe original wall ornaments.</p>\n<p>These ruins are as they were many hundreds of years ago, please avoid\ndisturbing the site or collecting artifacts so future generations can\nkeep enjoying the ruins.</p>\n<h2 id=\"approach\">Approach</h2>\n<p>From highway 261 take Snow Flat Rd heading east for 7.5 miles, you\nwill come to the trailhead for this hike. Fill out a a permit from the\nself-issuing permit station and proceed following the trail all the way\nto McLoyd canyon, where the cliff dwellings are located. If you have a\nhigh clearance vehicle you may drive on the road for the approach almost\nall the way to the canyon, saving 2 miles of walking.</p>\n<p>From the trailhead at the end of the road follow cairns for 0.5 miles\ndown into the McLoyd canyon and up to the obvious cliff dwellings. From\nthe main ruins proceed east onto the canyon cliffs to another set of\nwell conserved ruins at the same level. Then proceed back west, passing\nsome crumbling ruins and reaching the site of ancient petroglyphs, they\nare located high up on the canyon walls. The rangers told us there are\nsome baby footprints imprimpted on some of the petroglyphs but we could\nnot find them.</p>\n<h2 id=\"descent\">Descent</h2>\n<h2 id=\"exit\">Exit</h2>\n<h2 id=\"red_tape\">Red tape</h2>\n<p>A permit is required to visit the ruins. The current permit system\nlimits use to 20 people per day during the high season (March 1st - June\n15th, and September 1st - October 31st). Permits can be reserved in\nadvance by calling the Kane Gulch ranger station. Visiting in the off\nseason permits are required, but there is no limit, and they are\nextended via a self-pay envelope at the road turnoff to the ruins (see\nmap).</p>\n<p>More information is available on the BLM website <a\nhref=\"http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/monticello/recreation/places/cedar_mesa/MoonHouse.html\">http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/monticello/recreation/places/cedar_mesa/MoonHouse.html</a></p>\n<h2 id=\"beta_sites\">Beta sites</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><img src=\"rwl_en.png\" title=\"rwl_en.png\" alt=\"rwl_en.png\" /><a\nhref=\"http://roadtripryan.com/go/t/utah/cedar-mesa/moonhouse-ruin\">RoadTripRyan.com</a>\n: Moonhouse Ruin (McCloyd Canyon)</li>\n<li><a\nhref=\"https://utahscanyoncountry.wordpress.com/2013/06/20/moon-house-ruin/\">https://utahscanyoncountry.wordpress.com/2013/06/20/moon-house-ruin/</a></li>\n<li><a\nhref=\"http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/monticello/recreation/places/cedar_mesa/MoonHouse.html\">http://www.blm.gov/ut/st/en/fo/monticello/recreation/places/cedar_mesa/MoonHouse.html</a></li>\n<li><img src=\"rwl_en.png\" title=\"rwl_en.png\" alt=\"rwl_en.png\" /><a\nhref=\"http://climb-utah.com/CM/moonhouse.htm\">Climb-Utah.com</a> : Moon\nHouse Ruins</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"trip_reports_and_media\">Trip reports and media</h2>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n",
